Farewell lockdown, you were a challenge but you taught me so much…?
?
Okay so this is a little late, but with the UK slowly easing out of lockdown, I’ve spent a lot of time reflecting on what this turbulent phase has really taught me.?
?
I also had a little look through my Instagram as one of the main things I discovered in lockdown was my love for social media. I rediscovered the love for my blog and sharing my life online?
?
A little reintroduction later, I was back on Instagram - scroll through
?
We saw the first of the self-portraits and they quickly became a new form of creativity for me?
?
The outfit pictures then came, with a new and fresh layout. I’m so happy I discovered this little photo spot in my room. And also this shirt…?
?
It was then the beginning of my body positivity journey and sharing it with you all. I still remember how nervous I was to post this photo, but your encouragement and love keeps me making these posts now?
?
I found a love for fashion again and second hand clothes. As well as sewing and upcycling so many new pieces?
?
Oh and we also turned 18 in lockdown… kind of fun and all of your lovely messages meant the world to me?
?
And the first pictures is where we are now. Going outside and gaining some of that normality back??
?
I talk more about the real things I’ve learned in lockdown over on gracexkate.com but I just want to say how grateful I am for all of you. Those who followed during lockdown and those who have stuck around?
?
The best is yet to come!
G xx

Train your mind to see the good in every situation ?
.
.
.
.

Welcome to the next round of our digital meet&greet, this time with violist Katrin Spiegel who is studying with @barenboimsaidakademie's Prof. Yulia Deyneka. Learn more about this great arist here?
.
Q: The most important lesson I've learned as a musician:
A: To listen. The people you meet as a musician don't really care where you come from because it truly makes no difference. Playing chamber music means that you have to be able to listen, be sensitive, adjust, be able to discuss and help each other to reach the best level possible and do the best we can to make the experience enjoyable for the audience and for us, the musicians. 
.
Q: These three things got me through the lockdown:
The lockdown was a great time to reflect on our lives. I used this time to do more yoga and meditation, which in my opinion kept me sane in these stressful times. I practiced more and tried to develop my ability to use mental practice and planing better, and lastly, I kept in touch with the people I love the most.
.

As part of our lockdown diaries, we asked our followers about the new things they learnt during the lockdown. 
.
.
Here is what Mr. Tanveer Ahmed learnt during this period.
.
.
"As a student, reading is an important skill to have by your side. But when you're a CA student who has to read a ton, simple reading ain't gonna cut it. So I used the time I got during the lock down to learn how to speed read. Sounds simple right? Not quite! Takes a lot of practice before you can read fast and comprehend what you've just read. Now I can read about 235 words per minute.
.
.
We've all been affected by this pandemic. We've all been thinking that this would get up and just vanish one day. That seems highly unlikely now. From May onwards, Different Strokes have been delighted to be in conversation with individual stroke survivors in lockdown; discussing how they are coping, what they’ve found challenging and how this experience has impacted them in all aspects of day to day life. The pre-recorded interviews take place via Zoom and are posted every Tuesday afternoon. You can find them all on the Different Strokes website, Facebook page and YouTube channel - but over the next couple of weeks, a snippet of each already posted to the DS channels are going to be introduced to our wonderful Instagram audience, to give everyone a taster of personal affiliation with each survivor.⁣
⁣
Lockdown interview number five features stroke survivors Sheelagh and Belinda. Sheelagh is our Administrator at Different Strokes. She had her stroke in 2018 at the age of 51. Belinda had her stroke in 2015 at the age of 47. Belinda spoke to Sheelagh about her Neurofatigue, her process to recovery, the impact lockdown has had on that and how she’s had to adapt with having her Mum in the house when she still needs time alone to manage her condition. She also talks about the little things like how her shopping delivery has become a highlight, how she’s keeping occupied with crafting and colouring and the Different Strokes Facebook group being a game changer for her mentality and wellbeing.⁣
